english:
  title: A Further Reflection on the Inscription of the Jingglian Pavilion
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Tanggyeop's hermitage in Gwangju features a pond he dug himself, with lotus flowers planted around it. In the center of the pond, he raised earth to form a small island, and upon it he built a pavilion. Each day he ascends to find joy in contemplation. Minister Yi, known as Ikjae, named this pavilion the Jingglian—a tribute to the love of lotuses cherished by Lixi, the Master of Lianxi Stream. He wished that in beholding this place, one would admire and emulate that ancient sage.

    When we see a thing, we think of the person who loved it. When we think of that person, our hearts naturally turn to invest meaning in the thing itself. Thus does feeling deepen, and reverence grow complete.

    I have long observed that the ancients each held particular affections for flowers and grasses. Qu Yuan loved orchids, Tao Qian loved chrysanthemums, and Lixi loved lotus flowers. Each poured the contents of their inner being into these things, leaving traces both subtle and profound. The orchid possesses fragrant virtue; the chrysanthemum embodies the loftiness of reclusion. In these choices, we glimpse the hearts of these masters. Lixi himself declared: "The lotus is the gentleman among flowers." And he asked: "Who shares my love of the lotus?" To find joy in something and share it with others—this is the way of the sage. He lamented that his contemporaries did not understand him, and left his yearning to echo through endless ages to come.

    If one truly understands that the lotus is the gentleman, then perhaps one grasps the joy that Lixi himself knew. Yet to perceive the joy of sages and saints through contemplation of things—is this not a difficult attainment?

    Huang Luzhi observed that Zhou Maoshu's spirit was as clear and crystalline as fair wind beneath clearing skies. Cheng Yi recorded that upon meeting Zhou Maoshu, he was moved to seek out the joy known to Confucius and Yan Hui, to understand what they took pleasure in. Since that meeting, he said, I return humming in harmony with wind and moon, sharing the spirit of Zeng Dian.

    I myself believe that to honor Lixi requires a method: one must first grasp this crystalline clarity of spirit and cultivate the intent of Zeng Dian before one can truly speak of attainment. The inscription written by Minister Yi states: "Draw in the curtains and sit in stillness—wind and moon know no boundary." These lines capture an ancient truth. Oh, that I might once ascend that pavilion and commune there with him in this shared understanding!
  footnotes:
    - Lixi (濂溪) refers to Zhou Dunyi (1017-1073), a foundational Neo-Confucian philosopher also known as Master of Lianxi Stream, who wrote the influential 'Explanation of the Diagram of the Great Ultimate.'
    - Qu Yuan was the patriotic poet of ancient Chu who wrote of orchids as symbols of virtue.
    - Tao Qian (365-427), the recluse poet, famously cultivated chrysanthemums and wrote poetry celebrating them as embodiments of integrity.
    - Zeng Dian was the father of Confucius's disciple Zeng Can. In the Analects, Confucius approves Zeng Dian's response about his aspirations, which involve enjoying the simple pleasures of wind and water.
    - The inscription's final couplet encapsulates the aesthetic and spiritual ideal being discussed—the achievement of serene contemplation where the boundaries between self and nature dissolve.
